\begin_layout Standard
Here are a few questions that you should be able to answer based only on
 18.06:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{x}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 to have a solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 must be in the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, which is orthogonal to the left nullspace, which is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}^{*}\vec{m}=0$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}^{T}\vec{m}=0$
\end_inset

 for real vectors) is true if and only if a solution exists.
 If a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 exists, then all solutions are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}+\alpha\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 for any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 spans the nullspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be diagonalizable since it is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct eigenvalues.
 It need not be symmetric, however.
 (Real-symmetric implies real eigenvalues, but the converse is not true.
 For example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $A=V^{-1}\Sigma V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix of the eigenvalues, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is any real invertible matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is similar to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and so has the same eigenvalues, but is not symmetric unless 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is diagonalizable, its eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{1},\ldots,\vec{v}_{20}$
\end_inset

 (corresponding to the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\ldots,\lambda_{20}=-1,\ldots-20$
\end_inset

) form a basis, and we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\sum_{i}c_{i}\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)=e^{At}\vec{b}=\sum_{i}e^{\lambda_{i}t}c_{i}\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Because all the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $<0$
\end_inset

, these terms are exponentially decaying and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, for large finite 
\begin_inset Formula $t\gg1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)$
\end_inset

 will be dominated by the slowest-decaying term (the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 with a 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\ne0$
\end_inset

).
 The largest eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is random it is very unlikely that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)\approx e^{-t}c_{1}\vec{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)$
\end_inset

 will be approximately parallel to the eigenvector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-1$
\end_inset

 and will be decaying approximately as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
