\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: (10+10+5+10 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, we considered the 1d Poisson equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u(x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

 for the vector space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,L]$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dirichlet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=u(L)=0$
\end_inset

, and solved it in terms of the eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (giving a Fourier sine series).
 Here, we will consider a couple of small variations on this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All possible 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 do indeed form a vector space: this is just the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}/dx^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 More explicitly, recall that the column is a vector space because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u_{1}(x)=f_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u_{2}(x)=f_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 are possible right-hand sides, then clearly another possible right-hand
 side is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f_{1}+\beta f_{2}=\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}(u_{1}+u_{2})$
\end_inset

 for any scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 .
 However, it is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 the same as the vector space of the 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

, because the boundary conditions are not the same.
 For example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=x(L-x)$
\end_inset

, which vanishes at the endpoints and hence is in the vector space.
 Then the corresponding function in the column space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}x(L-x)=-2$
\end_inset

, which does not vanish at the endpoints.
 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u=\lambda u$
\end_inset

, it still follows (as in class) that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a sine, cosine, or exponential.
 Of these three possibilities, the only one with vanishing slope at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is cosine functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(kx)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 To have vanishing slope at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset

 as well, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 equal to an integer number of half-periods 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/L$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the eigenfunctions must be spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(n\pi x/L)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 is now a valid eigenfunction, whereas before we excluded this (since sine
 of zero was zero).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They do not form a vector space, since the space doesn't contain zero.
 Or, you could say that we cannot add, subtract, or multiply such functions
 by constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\neq1$
\end_inset

 without the result violating the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $v(L)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)$
\end_inset

 be any twice-differentiable function with 
\begin_inset Formula $q(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(L)=-1$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=v(x)+q(x)$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=u(L)=0$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=-x/L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=-\sin(\pi x/2L)$
\end_inset

 both work.
 Then substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=u(x)-q(x)$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}v(x)=g(x)$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u(x)=g(x)+\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}q(x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 In the two examples mentioned previously, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)+\left(\frac{\pi}{2L}\right)^{2}\sin(x/2L)$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Thus, if we solve the 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=u(L)$
\end_inset

 Poisson equation with this new right-hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, then we get back a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)+q(x)$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $v(L)=1$
\end_inset

 equation!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: (15+15 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now the null space consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=c$
\end_inset

 for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the Poisson solution, if it exists, is not unique: adding
 any constant yields another solution.
 Nor does the solution necessarily exist (even excluding crazy divergent
 right-hand-sides): from prolem 2(a), the eigenfunctions are now 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(n\pi x/L)$
\end_inset

, so if we can express the right-hand-side as a cosine series 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\sum_{n}a_{n}\cos(n\pi x/L)$
\end_inset

, a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\sum_{n}\frac{a}{-(n\pi/L)^{2}}\cos(n\pi x/L)$
\end_inset

 only exists of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{L}f(x)dx=0$
\end_inset

 (recalling the formula for the cosine series coefficients).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Without any boundary conditions, null space is any cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}x^{3}+a_{2}x^{2}+a_{1}x+a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Imposing 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Imposing 
\begin_inset Formula $u(L)=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=-a_{2}L+-a_{3}L^{2}$
\end_inset

, so we only have two remaining degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 (a two-dimensional null space).
 To make the null space 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, it is sufficient to add the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(0)=u'(L)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(0)=0$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=-a_{3}L$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(L)=0$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $2a_{2}+3a_{3}L=0=-2a_{3}L+3a_{3}L=a_{3}L$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 (It is still a vector space with these boundary conditions because they
 are zero: we can add, subtract, and multiply functions by constants while
 preserving the zero-slope property.) 
\end_layout

